================================================================
OSCP PRIVILEGE ESCALATION ENUMERATION COMMANDS
================================================================
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
WORLD-WRITABLE FILES
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null
 
Finds all files that any user can write to. Look for config
files, scripts, or anything sensitive like /etc/passwd or
cron scripts. A writable /etc/passwd means you can add a
new root user directly.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
WORLD-WRITABLE DIRECTORIES
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -writable -type d 2>/dev/null
 
Finds directories you can write to. Useful for dropping
files, replacing scripts, or planting payloads that cron
jobs might execute.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
SUID BINARIES
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -perm -4000 2>/dev/null
 
Finds binaries with the SUID bit set. These run as their
owner (often root) regardless of who executes them. Check
any unusual ones on GTFOBins (https://gtfobins.github.io).
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
SGID BINARIES
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -perm -2000 2>/dev/null
 
Same as SUID but for group permissions. The binary runs
with the group owner's privileges instead of the user's.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
BOTH SUID AND SGID
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -perm /6000 2>/dev/null
 
Finds binaries with either or both special permission bits
set. Broader sweep than searching for each individually.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
CAPABILITIES
----------------------------------------------------------------
getcap -r / 2>/dev/null
 
Lists binaries with special Linux capabilities assigned.
Look for cap_setuid which allows changing UID to root.
Once found, look it up on GTFOBins under Capabilities.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
UNMOUNTED DRIVES
----------------------------------------------------------------
cat /etc/fstab
mount
lsblk
 
/etc/fstab shows all configured drives including unmounted
ones. mount shows what is currently active. lsblk shows all
block devices. Look for unmounted partitions that might
contain sensitive data or credentials.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
CRON JOBS
----------------------------------------------------------------
cat /etc/crontab
ls -la /etc/cron.*
crontab -l
cat /etc/cron.d/*
cat /etc/cron.hourly/*
 
Shows all scheduled tasks. Look for scripts running as root
that are world-writable. If you can write to a script that
root runs via cron, you have root code execution.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
FILES WRITABLE BY YOUR GROUP
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -writable -type f -group $(id -gn) 2>/dev/null
 
Finds files writable by your current group. Useful when
you are in an interesting group like docker, lxd, or disk.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
ROOT-OWNED BUT WRITABLE FILES
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -user root -writable -type f 2>/dev/null | grep -v proc | grep -v sys
 
Root-owned files that you can still write to. A classic
misconfiguration that can lead to direct privilege escalation.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
READABLE CONFIG FILES (POTENTIAL CREDENTIALS)
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -name "*.conf" -readable 2>/dev/null
find / -name "*.config" -readable 2>/dev/null
find / -name "*.ini" -readable 2>/dev/null
 
Config files often contain plaintext passwords, API keys,
or database credentials that can be reused for escalation.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
RECENTLY MODIFIED FILES
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -mmin -10 -type f 2>/dev/null
 
Files modified in the last 10 minutes. Useful for tracking
cron job activity — run this and watch what changes to
identify scripts being executed by scheduled tasks.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
FILES WITH PASSWORDS IN THE NAME
----------------------------------------------------------------
find / -name "*password*" -o -name "*passwd*" -o -name "*cred*" 2>/dev/null
 
Hunts for files that might contain credentials based on
their filename. Quick win when admins store passwords in
obviously named files.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
SUDO PERMISSIONS
----------------------------------------------------------------
sudo -l
 
Shows what commands you can run as root or other users
without a password or with your current password. Always
run this first — it is the quickest and most common win.
Check any allowed binaries on GTFOBins under Sudo.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
CHECK USER GROUPS
----------------------------------------------------------------
id
groups
cat /etc/group | grep <username>
 
Being in certain groups leads to instant root:
- docker   -> mount host filesystem in container
- lxd/lxc  -> container escape to root
- disk      -> direct disk read/write access
- sudo      -> run commands as root
- adm       -> read sensitive log files
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
FIND ALL USERS WITH SHELLS
----------------------------------------------------------------
cat /etc/passwd | grep -v nologin | grep -v false
 
Shows all users that can actually log in. Useful for
identifying targets for lateral movement or password reuse.
 
----------------------------------------------------------------
CHECK ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
----------------------------------------------------------------
env
cat ~/.bashrc
cat ~/.bash_history
 
Environment variables sometimes contain credentials or
paths. Bash history often reveals passwords typed on the
command line or commands that reveal system structure.
 
